    </figure>
    </section>
    <section id="sect-00012">
    <title>Inserting a Table of Figures</title>
    <para id="para-00030">As with inserting a table of contents, first go to the top of your document where you will want your table of figures to appear. Typically, a table of figures is placed right below the table of contents. Now that we have labeled our table with a caption, we can create a table of figures to see how it works. As seen in <link target-id="fig-00012"/>, insert a page break, and choose the <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00028">Insert a Table of Figures</term> command from the References tab. Word will automatically “read” the existing captions, and a table of figures will be generated.</para>
    <para id="para-00031">To make your document neat and organized, add the title <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00029">Table of Figures</term> on top, and insert another page break to separate the Table of Figures page from the beginning of the document.</para>
    <figure id="fig-00012">
    <media alt="The Reference tab is selected on the Ribbon and in the Captions command group the Table of Figures button is selected. A Table of Figures pane is open with tabs available for Index, Table of Contents, Table of Figures and Table of Authorities. The Table of Figures tab is selected and displays a Print Preview window (which displays what is in the document) along with button options underneath for Show page numbers and Right align page numbers. A drop down menu for Tab leader follows next. A General heading with Formats and Caption label selections (with drop down menus) and a button option for Include label and number. At the right half there is a pane for Web Preview and a button option for Use hyperlinks instead of page numbers. Buttons for Options, Modify, OK and Cancel are located in two rows at the bottom right.">
