  </section>
    </section>
    </section>
    <section id="sect-00013">
    <title>Linked Bookmarks</title>
    <para id="para-00032">Another helpful tool for navigating long documents is the <term id="term-00030">bookmark</term>. You can add bookmark links throughout your document for better navigation. Place the cursor where you want the bookmark to link up to—a section header, for example, or the beginning of an important paragraph—and go to the Insert tab and click Bookmark. In the dialog box, type a name for your bookmark <link target-id="fig-00013"/>. In this case, we chose to bookmark the start of the body text. Now, select a word that will link up to the bookmark, right-click on it, and select <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00031">Hyperlink</term> from the context menu. The same hyperlink dialog box will appear, but this time select Place in This Document. Click on the bookmark you just made, and then click OK; the link will be set <link target-id="fig-00018"/>. Conversely, if you want to remove a bookmark from Word, click the <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00032">Bookmark</term> command in the Insert menu, locate it, and then select Delete.</para>
    <figure id="fig-00013">
    <media alt="A Links command group is visible and an arrow points to the Bookmark button within. A Bookmark pane is open and displays a text bar with bodytext typed inside. Checkable buttons for Sort by Name and Location are below as well as a selection button for Hidden bookmarks. At the top right are buttons for Add, Delete, and Go To and a Cancel button is visible at the bottom right.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OSX_BCA_04_03_BOOKMARKa.jpg"/>
    </media>
    <caption>When creating Bookmarks, make sure to choose a descriptor word that has meaning to the content you are designating. (attribution: Used with permission from Microsoft)</caption>
    </figure>
    <figure id="fig-00018">
      <media alt="An Insert Hyperlink pane is open and at the left offers options to Link to: Existing File or Web Page, Place in This Document, Create New Document, and E-mail Address. At the top is a space to enter Text to Display and a button for ScreenTip. A pane below offers locations to Select a place in this document (an outline of the document headers is visible in the pane) as well as a button on the right for Target Frame. OK and Cancel buttons are located at the bottom right.">
        <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OSX_BCA_04_03_BOOKMARKb.jpg"/>
              </media>
              <caption>The bookmark is now set. Linking a section of text to a bookmark eases navigation through a long document. (attribution: Used with permission from Microsoft)</caption>
            </figure>
    <para id="para-00033">Another reason to use bookmarks is to help digital readers of your document navigate back to important sections of the document while they read. For example, you can add a link at the end of each chapter that says, “Go to Table of Contents.” To do this, first place a bookmark in front of the table of contents as <link target-id="fig-00014"/> shows. To locate the roster of bookmarks, click the Bookmark command on the Insert tab, and then click Go to. If you want to relocate the bookmark, place the cursor where you want the bookmark to be relocated to, then open the Bookmark dialog box, click the original bookmark’s name, and then click Add. This will update the new location.</para>
    <figure id="fig-00014">
    <media alt="In the Table of Contents document, the cursor is located before the word Table. A pop up shows an Update Table button. A Bookmark Pane is open in front and lists the word tableofcontents in the Bookmark name bar. Add, Delete, and Go To buttons are on the right and Sort by Name and Location buttons are located below. A Hidden bookmarks button is available and a Cancel button is visible at the bottom right.">
